animal.description:
Meet fun and sweet Donna! Just looking at that super long tongue of hers should brighten your day! Donna had a rough start in life: she was living with a family until she was 3 m.o. until one day she jumped off a high bed and fractured her spine. The family didn't want to deal with these problems, so they dumped her outside of their apartments. The volunteers picked her up, did all the medical treatments and rehab until she fully recovered. Donna is 3y.9m. old shepherd mix. She is very human-oriented and food-driven (needs to lose some weight for that reason). She's lived in a few foster homes with adults, kids, dogs, cats and even 2 guinea pigs! She can stay home alone (with other dogs) without issues. Good on a leash and potty-trained. She is a quick-learner and knows quite a few basic commands in Russian. She may be a little possessive over her food with other dogs, but otherwise loves to run and play with them. Donna has medium level of activity with two walks, but would benefit from having a fenced-in yard to run around and exercise more throughout the day. She well-socialized and is gentle with little kids. She is curious about cats and may come up to smell them. Donna is about 66lbs and 24.5inches tall at the withers. Vaccinated, spayed and healthy. Donna is flying to the US mid-February and would love to have her forever family take her home!  Adoption fee is $600.

If you interested in adopting this girl, please fill out an adoption application: https://forms.gle/me4k8pMEdwSxbMwo7

"The future belongs to those who believe in the beauty of their dreams." My name is Claire Bear. I am a 1.5 year old, 70 pound Pit/Dane mix girl and I have been dreaming of a forever home to call my own. While waiting for my perfect home to come along, I have been working hard to make sure I am the best pup that I can be! I am already house trained and kennel trained, and I even know lots of commands, like "sit," "down," "shake," "speak," and many more! I get along great with other dogs, and would love to have a playful dog sibling in my forever home. I also do well with cats and kids, if you have either of those! I love to snuggle and chill in the house, but I also love to go for runs and hikes outside, so an active family would be best for me. Do I sound like your dream dog? Then fill out that application so that both of our dreams can come true!

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Thor will be arriving in 2 weeks.
Shelter staff report that he is a fun loving big fellow who loves to finally have freedom. Breed guesses: Black Mouth Cur, Redbone Coonhound, Labrador

This is his backstory as told by the shelter:
This dogs owner died in December leaving this 8 year old with no one since. The daughter was trying her best to keep him fed and watered but live in a kennel and seems that’s how owner kept him was all bottled up.  The city of Senath ACO was zero help. This dog was abandoned inside a house with no electric and still nothing was going to be done. A neighbor was worried he would jump through windows and hurt himself so she asked for help. What fucking city let’s a dog stay like that?  All that had to be done was to surrender the dog over. Anyway 
We didn’t know type of dog or what we were getting into until we saw the truck coming with tarps over a wire kennel reinforced with chicken wire and this poor dog was riding in that. 
Thor came out bouncing and happy to be on ground. Daughter says he was good with the other small dogs in the house her dad had (those dogs died I’m told). 
Thor is at least 8 and my best guess 100-120 lbs 
You can see the injuries on his head and face from trying to get out of kennels 
He has had zero vetting 
Becky was gracious to offer to bring him to her pound at least has heat food and water. 
Thor really needs to be in boarding so I’m looking for donations to help with that. 
I’m praying someone will see the good in this boy.

animal.description:
Boomer is a super sweet and goofy boy. He loves to run the back yard and play with his foster siblings. After a good hard play he is ready for a nice nap. He is content curling up by himself or laying with a foster sibling, but his true joy is cuddling up with his people. He does well in the house and hasn't had any accidents. He is crate trained and doesn't cry or tear up things while crated. He has gotten along well with two other male dogs his size in the home. He also does well on car rides. He walks well on a leash and knows how to sit. 

Boomer came to us after he became urgent at the shelter. Boomer was impounded by animal control on 11/19/2020 after someone reported that he got out of his fenced yard and bit someone on the ankle while they were working outside. Boomer stayed in the shelter until 1/14/21 where he had no issues with any of the staff or other animals. Boomer went into a foster home on 1/14/21, where he has done phenomenal and has had no issues. Unfortunately due to Boomer's bite record inside the City limits of Sapulpa, he can not be adopted to anyone that lives inside Sapulpa city limits. 

Boomer previously lived with children and a small dog. He did well and had no issues with his previous family. Boomer is a very active dog and his new home will require a fenced in yard so he is able to safely run/play. 
When Boomer was impounded it was said that he jumped the chain link fence to get out but we can't confirm this. He has had no issues with trying to escape his fosters yard, however a home with a privacy fence is necessary for Boomer. 

Boomer's estimated date of birth is 7/14/19, he is 50lbs, neutered, current on all vaccinations, dewormed, on flea/tick prevention, heartworm negative and on prevention. Boomer is also microchipped and will come with a new ID tag when adopted. 

Boomer is currently in a foster home. Meet and greets can be scheduled by appointment once an approved application is on file. 
Applications can be found on our website: www.sapulpafurryfriends.org

Come Meet Our Adoptable Dogs...
Winnipeg Animal Services Agency
1057 Logan Avenue
Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada
R3E 3N8

Phone: 311 - outside Winnipeg dial 1-877-311-4974 

Email: animalservicesagency@winnipeg.ca

Our hours for adoption are Monday to Friday from 11:00 am - 5:30 pm
Saturday & Sunday from 12:00 pm - 4:30pm.
Animal Services is closed on statutory holidays.

BACKGROUND
Almost all the dogs at Animal Services are picked up as strays running loose on the streets of Winnipeg and therefore they come to us with no known history. All locally adopted dogs come with a 7 day home trial. If you return the dog within this time period, you will be refunded your adoption fee less the non-refundable deposit.

Please feel free to meet all the dogs and puppies outside of their kennels, just let the kennel attendants know that you would like a meet and greet with the dog outside of his pen. The dogs are much more relaxed when outside of their kennels. They would love to meet you!

animal.description:
Sammy: hes the goofball of the group. Hes clumsy because his long legs get in the way! He is probably the most active of the 3. His ears always have that adorable dorky look!

Sammy was found roaming with 2 other huskies, who we belive are his siblings. The finder brought them home and has done an incredible job of taking care of them and training them! We believe them to be between 1-2 years of age. 

 

 

 

Here is some information their foster has shared about him and his siblings: 

 

All dogs seem to have grown up together but are not bonded and can be adopted separately. They did better than I thought they would do getting baths as long as you go slow and talk to them! They did so great at the dog park. They are learning different ways to play (when they play together they are boys but my brothers female dog Lucy doesnt play rough) Did not seem to know basic commands but have been working on sit and off (jumping). They are required and successfully sit for 15-30 seconds (depending on my mood) before their food is placed in front of them for breakfast and dinner. Not food aggressive at all! As a matter of fact each dog will stop eating to show you attention if you ask them for it. I was able to put my hand in the bowl while they are each eating without fear. Individually each dog met my cats but completely supervised and controlled. Together they seem to want to play with my 10 year old cat and its just too much causing him to run and them to give chase. I have separate inside time between my cats and the dogs. We are doing much better about accidents in the home. The first week they had 4 plus accidents a day. Now have only had 2 accidents in the past 3 weeks. They (Rogue and Sammy) when left alone and bored they chew on whatever is lying around, definitely need a job to do or lots of fun toys or Kong's! Thankfully they do not constantly bark and dont bark at absolutely everything (park on other side of chain link fence where kids and other dogs walk) but are always alert. They love fetch and we are working on the returning part in the game of fetch.

Sammy would love to be part of any family and being a husky would like a family that is active or has a back yard for him to play in.

He is up to date on vaccines according to his age, has received proper deworming, and comes with additional dewormer. He is microchipped, neutered, comes with 6 months of preventatives, one month free trial of pet insurance, all of our animals receive a health certificate (this states a licensed veterinary saw the pet and deemed it healthy for travel, it is not a promise of perfect health.) Our transports are USDA certified and tfransport is included in adoption fee!

 

He is currently being fostered in Houston, Tx but will be traveling to the PNW 2/6/21.

Please inquire by submitting an application to mariah@threelittlepittiesrescue.org

Application link: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/26842/generic

animal.description:
**WE ONLY DO HOME VISITS FOR ADOPTIONS NEAR BROWARD & PALM BEACH COUNTIES**

COQUITO IS WAY HEALTHIER THAN EXPECTED BUT HE IS STILL SPECIAL NEEDS! Coquito's previous people could not afford his medical care and he was on death's door when we rescued him. He was not expected to make it but we have completed months of rehab to get him to a seemingly healthy state. We have done a couple of thousand dollars of diagnostics and treatments. His liver is still enlarged but his liver values are NORMAL He has collapsed trachea but has not had any symptoms since the thyroid meds kicked in. He is on thyroid tabs, joint meds, two eye drops, and supplements. He is doing phenomenally well. We are putting him up for adoption to a qualified home. He is 11 years old, 5.5 pounds, he will potty on wet grass, something chihuahuas are not fond of! LOL!, He cuddles and asks for attention with his paws. Coquito is quiet and good with dogs under 15 pounds. He initiates play with the other dogs. COQUITO IS SPECIAL NEEDS AND WILL NEED DAILY MEDICATION, REGULAR VET VISITS TO MONITOR HIS THYROID! PLEASE ONLY APPLY IF YOU HAVE THE TIME AND FINANCES TO CONTINUE THE CARE WE HAVE PROVIDED. No Children. Check this link for his video playlist His adoption fee is $150 to go towards his vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, and microchip as well as grooming if needed).

Please read his daily needs and check pricing with your vet for the thyroid tests and x-rays so you know what to expect.

 

He is calm and cuddly once he trusts you but he will freak out and hold his breath when being held by some people in new environments. This stress causes him to lose oxygen and his tongue turns blue. If he is not relieved from his stress quickly he will need oxygen by a vet. When he is getting his tests ran we plan a couple of hours so he can rest in between tests and not be gasping to breathe. 

 

FOOD

He is on Dave's brand low protein and low phosphorus canned food with a teaspoon of Dave's brand joint formula just to get him to eat the low protein food. It is important he doesn't eat other treats except for some veg, because of the high protein is hard for his liver and pancreas to digest.

 

MEDICATIONS

He gets 1/2 Galliprant once a day for arthritis which is a lifelong prescription for pain and inflammation. 

He also needs Gabapentin for pain once daily.

He is on Thyro tabs 1.5 grams twice a day and needs a thyroid blood test every 6 months.

His ophthalmologist has him on two eye drops for the ulcers caused by the thyroid issue. Currently, both drops are only for one eye but eventually, it will be for both eyes.

He is on Sentinal brand monthly heartworm prevention for under 10 pounds. He has not had a reaction to this brand so he must only continue with it.

 

SUPPLEMENTS

*He gets pre & probiotics in his food once a day to help with his digestion and fiber in the opposite meal to keep his bowels working..He gets blocked up easily which makes him painful and triggers a nerve that affects his neck and right front leg. 

*He gets joint supplements once a day from Zesty paws brand. 

*He is not on flea and tick prevention because we don't have a problem and he is sensitive so we give him ECO Flea once a day. He loves it! 

*He also gets an immune supplement once a day. 

*He gets pulse antibiotic therapy with Clindymysin 4-5 days twice a day at the beginning of each month to keep the oral infection down since he is not able to go under anesthesia for a dental cleaning. due to his collapsed trachea. He currently doesn't have any symptoms of coughing from the trachea. Keeping the infection down is crucial to helping his other organs function better and less oral pain from inflammation. During those few days, he doesn't get the probiotics.

 *He gets liver supplements that helped get his liver values in a good range on his bloodwork. This is another precaution so he keeps up his health.

 

GROOMING

He needs to be groomed at home in short periods of time because he stresses and again loses oxygen with the collapsed trachea. Once he trusts you, you will need to gently maneuver him to get him cleaned up. He can't have anything around his neck, because of the trachea. He needs his paws and privets groomed for cleanliness and a better grip on the floor. His chest also gets food on it sometimes so I groom his body to even out his lion's mane! LOL! There are YouTube videos to guide you.

 

This regime is only a fraction of what saved his life. Scientifically and physically she wasn't going to live the first few days we had him. He has been through a battery of tests, treatments, and meds to get him to adoptable status in 6 months.

 

He will need a dedicated caregiver to follow through with his needs and continue with proper vet care at an established vet, not a vaccine clinic.

 

We get a lot of people interested in Coquito's cuteness but they don't understand the commitment. We are no-kill, foster home only so all our dogs are free to run in foster homes sleeping in our beds and getting all their needs met. We are hopeful for Coquito and all our other special needs dogs will all get qualified homes, but if not they can be in our forever foster care program. He will always be safe and properly cared for. Please think this through, get information from your vet on the cost of tests and look online for the cost of meds plus supplements. He has a quality of life with this regimen. Please let me know if you truly feel you can fulfill his needs. 

 

NEW

Recently he had a stroke at the ophthalmologist and went blind, had a hard time walking and eating. That lasted 3-4 days and he was back to normal. We ran his bloodwork and other tests that all came out fine. His heart is good. It must have been the stress at the ophthalmologist because they had to hold him for the exam. Next time he will get a sedative to prevent the stress.

If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check our FAQ's Page. 

 *All dogs in the care of Get a Life Pet Rescue live in loving foster homes while waiting for their perfect match. They don't live in cages or crates (unless there is a medical reason to do so.) They are treated as family pets while in our care. * All dogs in our care are fed premium brand holistic food as well as supplements and vitamins specific to each dog's needs. We don't buy inexpensive bulk dry kibble, our rescues are fed premium wet food diets as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program to ensure maximum health.*All of our rescues receive complete quality vetting including full dental cleaning with pre-op bloodwork, spay/neuter, vaccines, and grooming. Dogs in need of specialized medicine will be seen by specialists, such as full cardiac workups, ophthalmologist visits, all suspicious lumps, and bumps are biopsied, and every medical need is transparent to potential adopters. *Once you adopt from Get a Life Pet Rescue, you become part of our compassionate family and we are here for you if a problem with your precious dog arises.

animal.description:
Dallas is a GORGEOUS Black Lab mix who is 1-2 years old, weighs 66 lbs, and is in IMMEDIATE NEED of a FOSTER!  He was wandering for a week with a heavy chain around his neck and at one point was witnessed being clipped by a car before one of our BarkVille volunteers became aware of him and was involved with helping a team of good samaritans safely capture him.  They brought him back to their house and contacted animal control, but when they saw the extent of his injuries, they got him vetted, neutered and vaccinated.  They learned that Dallas is Heartworm positive, but thankfully, animal control allowed Dallas to stay in the family's home until his stray hold was up so that he didn't have to be in the shelter. Now that Dallas is available for adoption, BarkVille is looking for a foster home so that we can raise the necessary funds to treat his HW disease and find Dallas the loving, forever home he deserves!

Dallas is a super sweet boy and will be a wonderful family dog.  He loves tennis balls and all things "TOY."  He is crate trained, gets along fine with the other dogs he has met and is currently working on his house training.  If you are not familiar with Heartworm disease, dogs get it from mosquitos and it is not contagious. It is highly treatable, but requires extended rest during treatment.

For more information about Dallas, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet boy, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
Ziggy is a fun loving 7 month old 35 pound active puppy who enjoys playing with toys, going for walks and romping around with his dog friend in his foster home. His favorite game is chasing a toy at the end of a fishing pole which is great fun and burns a lot of energy. His specialty is being able to sleep in any position. Ziggy is smart dog who would love a home with an active owner who will take him on adventures and spend time keeping up his training and keeping him entertained. A fenced yard is a must and another playful dog would be the icing on the cake!

 

To meet Ziggy n the fluff visit our website for more details regarding our adoption criteria and complete the easy online no obligation adoption application at www.dsda.org/adopt. 

* Adoption Fees:

Puppies (12 months and under) - $325 (includes tax)

Dogs (over 12 months) - $275 (includes tax) 

Qualifications for Adoption: No dog is alike and each dog has different requirements based on breed, age, energy level and life experiences. DSDA is very careful to place our dogs in homes that we believe are the best fit for the dog based on our experience with each dog. All of our dogs live in foster homes which allows us the opportunity to learn about their individual needs. 


	Must be 21 years or older with identification showing present address.
	Must have the knowledge and consent of all adults living in the household.
	Vet checks are required. All resident animals must be spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations and on monthly heartworm and flea/tick preventative (if applicable).
	Must receive proof of pet deposit and lease allowing pets if renting.
	Willingness and capacity to spend the time and money necessary to provide training, medical treatment and responsible care for a pet.
	Applicant is home more than not.
	Any poisonous plants must be removed from the yard before the home visit.
	Home visit is required. For this reason, we adopt locally in the Dallas and immediate surrounding areas.

I get so much attention! But if no one notices me, I really will chew them up. Haha! At my appointment this past week I was almost 42 pounds. If you are looking for a sweet gentle dog to love, I am your girl.

animal.description:
Malachai was surrendered by his owner when she took him to the vet because of a tumor on his leg. The vet told her that he would have to have the leg removed due to the size and invasiveness of the tumor. She didn't want to do that so she elected to surrender him to a rescue. We got him to NY from Texas and were horrified by the size of the tumor and the amount of pain he was in. 
Even though he was in pain he was so sweet and loving. We got him into the surgeons office and they agreed that amputation was the only option for our little boy. They kept him and did the surgery that day. Malachai rocked his surgery and was standing up as soon as his anesthsia wore off!!!!! We also suspected that he had bladder stones and that was sonfirmed as well. The vet said that the bladder surgery would have to done at another time because of the dangers of extended time under anesthesia so they will be taken care of in about two weeks. 
You don't meet many pups with the personality and demeanor of this little man. He is just the sweetest boy in the world. He is already on the move and it seemed he was relieved to have the leg gone that was causing him so much pain. It has been sent out for a biopsy and we know that the lines will be clear around the site of the tumor. He is destined to have a wonderful life. Please say a prayer for this handsome little tripod. 
Malachai has been through so much for a pup that is only 8 years old and around 10lbs. He truly deserves the best that life has to offer. Don't think of him as handicapped, because he doesn't think of himself that way. He is happy and loving and perfect in our eyes. 
Malachai is located in Freeport NY
His adoption fee is $600

Please consider that some of these dogs have been abandoned or ignored by their previous owners, having little interaction with someone who cares about them.

When adopted, they will need time to adjust to the changes in their life.

Hi, my name is KimBella, and I'm a pretty, approximately four year old female GSD/Hound (?) mix who was transferred to FRGSR after someone found me running loose, pregnant and very hungry. This kind person took the time to rescue me and then took me to a shelter where I could receive some much-needed help. Very shortly thereafter, I delivered eight beautiful puppies (2 females and 6 males). I'm a sweet, devoted mom who is now living comfortably in a foster home where I'm receiving regular meals so I can take care of my babies. My foster mom says I know some basic commands and I've learned how to go potty outside. More info to come as I settle in. If you are interested in giving me my furever home, please go to adoptagsd.org and submit an online application. My adoption fee is $300. If you are interested in one of my puppies, they will be available in mid-March. Please submit an online application so the FRGSR team can get it processed.

Although we do our best to keep our adoptable animals page as current as possible,the animals you see may already be in an adoption process.

animal.description:
COURTESY POST!  VAL IS NOT A SOHO DOG.  IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN LEARNING MORE ABOUT HIM PLEASE EMAIL HIS OWNER DIRECTLY AT rehomeval@gmail.com.  
Val is a Cattle Dog/Heeler mix who needs to find a new home.  He is 6 years old, weighs 50-55 pounds, and he has a black/white/brindle coat – very unusual!  Val is neutered and up to date on his vaccines.  He is housebroken, walks OK on a leash and loves to ride in the car.  Val also knows several obedience commands.
Val loves his family but he is a bit standoffish when he first meets someone new.  Once he gets to know someone, though, he is always excited to see them!  While he does well with adults, children make him nervous.  Val is not playful with other dogs and never takes the lead in trying to meet a new dog.  His favorite things to do are all with people – he loves to run, take walks, go on camping trips, “patrol” the yard, wade in the nearby creeks and play tug-of-war.  Val will “alert bark” when someone comes to the door or when a car drives up to the house.  Val gets along great with cats!
The ideal home for Val is a quiet, friendly one, shared with adults who are looking for a loyal, fun-loving dog to share their time at home and their adventures.  A fenced yard is important, regular walks or hikes would be fabulous, cats are welcome, and the best home for him has no other dogs and no children.  He likes a stable, predictable routine!  Val has so much personality and love to share with the right family.  He currently lives in Asheville, NC, and you can contact his owner at rehomeval@gmail.com.

animal.description:
"I'll be a big dog soon." Hey there, my name is Atlas. It won't be too long before I am living up to my name. I'm a Great Pyrenees and Anatolian mix, and you know what you get when you mix those two, right? You get a big dog, maybe weighing about 120 lbs. At the moment, I am 58 lbs, and was born around August 2020.

I was an owner surrender when The Great Pyrenees Rescue Society rescued me. My family bought me for a livestock guardian, and they moved into the city and didn't need me anymore. But I have gotten over it and have decided I want to live with humans.

My safe place is in my crate. I'm working on my house training and walking nicely on a leash. I prefer to run with the big dogs, and I would be an excellent third dog in a multi-dog pack near my size. The bigger the pack, the better, as I love playing with tug toys with these guys. I love to chew on my toys, and sometimes I chew stuff I am not supposed to, sorry.

I am a little shy, therefore, I would thrive in an active home with older considerate kids and a couple of big resident canine companions to show me the ropes. I am smart, affectionate, and need confident leaders in my family familiar with Pyr/Anatolian traits and behaviors. If you have room in your home and heart for a big dog to be, complete an Adoption Application today.

PUPPIES ARE ONLY PLACED IN HOMES WITH YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL RESIDENT DOGS.

Our requirements for puppy adoption are simple and necessary.

	Our puppies are not livestock guardians, they are family pets that live inside the family home.
	Puppies must be placed in homes with a youthful, adult resident dog of similar size. This gives the puppy a mentor and a solid foundation for becoming part of the family.
	Puppies are only adopted to homes with someone at home at least part of the day. If no one is home for 6-8 hours at a time, please do not apply.
	Preference is always given to those with Great Pyrenees experience.
	Applicants must have secure, visible fencing and a socialization plan in place.
	The fastest way to be considered for a puppy is to fill out an application. Adoption is not first come, first served. GPRS and its fosters work diligently to find the right fit for each and every unique dog and puppy.
	Applicant's personal pets must be current on vaccines & heartworm/flea prevention and be altered.

Adoption Fee: $450 (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org/

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

animal.description:
Nala is a beautiful girl that was left at our vets office and has been there for over a year. She is such a sweet girl and didn't deserve to get dumped by her former people. 
Nala is 9 years old but in excellent health. She has so many years of life and so much joy to give to a family of her very own. 
Nala's only issue is that she absolutely must be an only pet!! We cannot stress this enough! She has a very high prey drive and does not do well with any animals. This means all animals. Cats, dogs, hamsters, gerbils, ferrets, birds, well you get the idea. 
This precious sweet girl has been living in the managers office at the vet practice and on holidays is there all by herself. Can you imagine not having a home of your own for the holidays? While all the other pups are opening their presents and enjoying their stockings, while they are getting goodies from the leftovers of the holiday feasts she is alone in the office. 
Please don't get us wrong, she is adored by the entire staff. She spends her days getting spoiled and pampered. But the nights are long and lonely and the holidays are the same. 
All we wish is for her to have her very own feast and her very own presents. Somewhere she will be safe and loved for the rest of her days. 
Nala is what's considered a Pocket Pittie. She is around 32lbs but is probably in need of a little diet because everyone spoils her with cookies. 
If you are interested in giving this magnificent angel her perfect home please email us for an adoption application at ourbestfriendsrescue@gmail.com
Nala is located in Sayville NY
She is fully vetted and will have her teeth cleaned before she leaves to go home. 
She is spayed, housebroken and microchipped

animal.description:
"Patience is more than learning to wait; it is having learned what is worth your time." My name is Axton and, if you show me a little patience, I will reward you with a lifetime of love. I am a 3 year old, 60 pound Pit mix boy. I may take a little time to warm up to new people, but once I know I can trust you I am a sweet and snuggly boy. I am looking for a dog savvy owner who can help provide me with the boundaries and training I need to be my most confident self. I LOVE going for rides in the car and promise to be a great copilot if you take me along on your adventures; I would even be a great companion for a truck driver! I do well with smaller dogs with proper introductions, but I would also do great as your one and only furry family member. I am looking for a home without cats or kids, as both make me a little too nervous. I am a smart boy who is already house trained and kennel trained, and I know some basic commands too (just be sure to have lots of treats for my training practice). If I sound like the perfect boy for you, then fill out that adoption application; I'll be waiting patiently for our forever to start!

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Lil and I'm the sweetest 6-year-old girl you'll ever meet! There's nothing that I love more than spending every waking moment with my human. I'll follow you around everywhere and I love going on hiking adventures, swimming, supervising yard work or even just hanging out in the house and napping on the couch. (As long as I'm within one foot of my person.) 

I'm a really good girl and I've never chewed anything up or run away from home. I'm a big snuggler and will need a home that lets me on the furniture and maybe even in bed with them. I know how to use a treadmill! I get along with other dogs well enough, but mostly I only care about my humans. I go to doggy daycare and have some doggy siblings that I get along well with. Unfortunately, one of my doggy siblings is a herding dog that felt the need to keep biting me, so I finally nipped back and now I need to find a new home. I like boy dogs more than girl dogs. 

I don't know how well I'd get along with kids, since I've never really spent much time around them. I'm not a good fit for small animals, like bunnies, since I am a hunting dog and have been known to hunt them. My prey drive isn't strong enough to take me out to a field to flush pheasants though. 

Basically, I need a family that is going to spoil me to bits and never wants to go into a room alone again!

animal.description:
The Cable Guy never looked so goodso Jim Careymove on over and welcome the guy would want to come and fix anything in your houseand stay furever! Cable is an adorable tan and white hound come lab mix who is a friend to everything from the dogs to the fences, he doesn't really care he just seems so happy to have landed at SG and living the life of a cared for dog. Cable is about a year or so old and about 50 lbs, a little on the lean side and happy for some extra snacks to fatten up a bit and settle in to a regular routine of care and attention. There is no convincing him he isn't a lap dog and he loves to cuddle as well as give and receive affection. Cable can be a bit shy at first, but more in the teasing and playful kind of way and would fit in easily and begin to show his silly and fun side quickly once he knows he is home. He would do well in a home with another dog to help show the way and would love a fenced-in yard, though it certainly is not a requirement. He is a fast learner who rides great in the car, was quick to figure out how a doggy door works and walks pretty well on leash. Cable is sure to bring laughs galore and be a comedy in and of himself. Turn on that computer and put that app in ASAP!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Mimi is a beautiful pit bull mix, all black in colour who is about 3 years
old and 19kgs. 
She was abandoned in the streets of Guadalajara,
Mexico and now lives at a dog rescue/sanctuary in Puerto Vallarta
with 20 other dogs! She was friendly to all the dogs upon arrival and
did not show any shyness or timidity when meeting them. However,
she was quite nervous to meet us volunteers after her abandonment
and mistreatment from humans before. After a short amount of time,
she warmed up and started giving all the hugs and kisses. 
Mimi is just as happy to play as she is to snuggle up and nap. She has been
through a lot and has remained so tender and sweet through it all.
On walks and at home she has not shown aggression, just a little
timidity. 
When hearing dogs bark or large traffic, Mimi will stop and
need some positive reassurance to continue. She is used to walking
with other dogs and is especially fond of the medium to large size
male dogs for play mates. 
Mimi is an absolute delight to have around, very easy going, potty-trained and quite calm. When given the proper love and care Mimi will surely bring so much happiness and joy to you everyday. Mimi is so beautiful and loving and
deserves the absolute best in life.

Mimi can be on our next flight into Seattle once an adoptive home is found.

If you are interested in adopting Mimi, please reply with some info about yourself/ your home

animal.description:
Anna is a very pale fawn 3 year old female found as a stray by a Good Samaritan who contacted PugHearts.

She is very quiet and sweet, and though timid at first, but will perk up and run around the yard, wagging her tail and mingling with any pugs and people present. Also in typical pug fashion, she loves food and treats. She has decent leash manners and is also a champion at outside potties, even in the rain!! She crates well but I think would also do well left out. She has shown no interest in toys yet. She does give the occasional comical exposed underbite grin. She is such an easy girl to live with, and pleasant to all who meet her, once she warms up to them. Anna will need someone who can love her to confidence, and continue this pampered life she should always have known.

Anna is heartworm negative, and we're treating some minor intestinal and skin issues. She will be home ready after spay, toward the end of 2/2021. Meantime follow her updates on Facebook and Instagram.

Like all puppies will need patience and consistency to master house training and manners (typically takes 3-6 months to master). Puppies are a lot of work but so rewarding! 
Adoption fee is $250 it includes spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations, rabies license, microchip, dewormer, heart worm preventative for the month, vet exam. Please go like our Facebook page at http://www.facebook.com/barkandroll . Follow us on instagram/twitter @barkandrollrc to see more pictures of me as well as other dogs in our rescue. You can access an adoption application on our website http://www.barkandrollrescuecompanions.com It usually take 1-2 days to complete the application process.

animal.description:
This pretty girl is named Sheba. She is a medium-sized three year old Bulldog-mix, and her short coat is brindle and white. Sheba tested positive for heart worm when she was examined by the veterinarian, so she has begun a treatment regimen. She can be adopted while still in treatment, but it's important that she have only strictly limited physical activity.
The adoption fee covers the spay/neuter surgery, a 1-year rabies shot, a da2ppv shot (canine distemper/parvo vaccine), heartworm test, deworming and microchip.

Carroll County Animal Shelter is located at 251 Automation Drive in Carrollton GA.
The hours of operation are: Monday 12:00-5:00; Tuesday and Wednesday 8:00-5:00; Thursday 10:00-7:00; Friday 8:00-5:00; Saturday 8:00-4:00; Closed Sundays.
Phone: 770-214-3590

animal.description:
Please welcome Foster Chico to PugHearts. Chico came to PugHearts as an owner surrender through no fault of his own. Chico is an adorable, low-riding 4-year-old pug mix looking for his very own happily ever after. We were told he’s a Chug, but there might be a little bit of Puggle or something else mixed in there. His front paws have the most adorable “turned out” stance, so maybe he’s training to be a dancer?

So far, Chico is getting along well with his foster siblings as well as the kids and people in his foster home. He’s a little shy and reserved, so we’re looking forward to seeing him come out of his shell once he gets a little more comfortable. He has been doing excellent with his house manners but does like to climb. Chico sleeps well in his crate overnight and has been a pretty chill and calm houseguest so far. We know he needs to gain some weight and go for his neuter, but we’ll know more about any other medical needs once he sees our vet for his intake exam. If you’re looking for a sweet and chill companion, with adorably large ears, Chico may be your perfect match!

animal.description:
Hellllo friends, it's me - Charlie Chaplin! I'm approximately 12 years old but don't let my age fool you, I am VERY active and strong. I weigh about 80 pounds and I am ready to sniff-sniff-sniff and follow my nose on all kinds of adventures, WITH YOU! I thoroughly enjoy going for long walks. Want a hiking buddy? I'm in, I'm no couch potato! In fact, I do very well in doggie daycare and would thrive in an active home with or without other dogs. Sorry, no cats, they are just too much fun for this ol' hound boy to chase.

I really LOVE being around people most of all and will lovingly follow you around. I love food, second-best to people! OK, maybe it's a tie! I am not food aggressive at all, but when I smell food - any kind of food - I get very excited and will do anything I can to get to the source of that wonderful smell! My foster mom crates me when she's cooking, for some reason she doesn't want my help! She also crates me when she's not at home, this stops me from helping myself to pantry - darn!

See, I am originally from Kentucky and was found as a stray. My foster mom surmises that I never lived in a home before and that I was an "outside dog" so all of the luxuries of a home environment were new to me when I arrived. I have been in my foster home since August though so I have learned so much! Yup, I'm ready for a forever family to take me the rest of the way! So whattya say?

Are you ready for some forever fun, with me?! Great! Please fill out an application today at www.northstarpets.org and ask for CHARLIE CHAPLIN!

NOTE: Charlie is NOT with 11th Hour Rescue but we are helping to network him for an adopter or even a foster home.

animal.description:
Ollie is an active 1-year-old, so he needs to have a fenced yard. Ollie very much loves playing and running around in a fenced yard. He really likes stuffed toys. When you hold him, he snuggles in and wants to be as close to you as he can.
Ollie was a stray prior to his rescue, so he's still learning to walk on a leash and needs work on coming when called in from the yard. Right now, he thinks it's a fun game that inspires you to play and chase him. Ollie also likes playing with other dogs.
Ollie may be compatible with cats. He did not react when introduced to a cat. He would need further testing to see if he'd chase a running cat.
If you have kids in the home, they should be 8 or older. Ollie is still a little mouthy, but we're working on that. With a little patience and training, Ollie will be well on his way to great little life-long companion.
Age: 1 year
Weight: 21 lbs
Vetting: Neutered, up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative
Temperament: Good with dogs and possibly cats; ok with older kids (8+).

Knock knock, it’s me, Hank. Aka Prince Charming. I’m a young and cute Great Pyrenees who loves people and gets along with dogs, cats and people. I’m looking for my own family to love, kiss and play with. My foster mom says that I’m very smart, learn new commands in an instant and am a pleaser. I seem to be house trained and knows basic commands. I do love food and tend to jump on the the countertop to get it.
 
Foster mom and the vet say I was born with “bad conformation” or structure. I get around and play, but I’m sometimes wobbly and hesitant on stairs. animal.description:
*INQUIRIES SENT THROUGH PETFINDER WILL NOT BE ANSWERED. PLEASE COMPLETE OUR ADOPTION APPLICATION INSTEAD*

Sully-IL is in a foster home in Kirkland, IL. Please read ALL the information in his listing before applying. If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for him, please complete our adoption application at http://www.idogrescue.com/adoption_application. We will review your application & let you know if you made our short list of applicants. We base our adoption decisions on what’s in the best interest of our dogs. Please note our adoption policies are in place for the safety & welfare of our dogs.

We are all volunteers & have jobs, families, pets of our own to care for. We believe in taking time to go through our thorough process to try to match the dog with the best fit for that dog. Our adoption process may take 2-4 weeks. You must be approved to adopt before we will schedule a meet & greet. We expect approved adopters to visit him in his foster home within a short period of time of being approved to adopt him. Our adoption process involves vet & personal reference checks, phone interviews, a home visit, an adoption contract & an adoption fee.

*We expect to have a lot of interest in Sully. Please do NOT apply unless you meet the requirements listed below. We also will not transport him.
- Experienced & active family who is willing to take him through formal training to ensure he becomes the best dog
-Kids 12+ who are used to large bratty puppies
- Where he gets to exercise his brain through daily physical & mental exercise to burn his puppy energy 
- Fenced yard
- With a younger, tolerant dog or as an only dog
- Where he isn’t crated for long periods of time & can he get exercise, attention
 
AGE: 17 weeks 
WEIGHT: 27 lbs. & still growing - will be a large adult likely around 70 lbs.
FENCE REQUIREMENT: A physical secure privacy fence is required. No electronic fence or e-collar will be allowed as we feel this would not set him up for success.
COAT TYPE: Sully has a soft, wavy coat that is currently lower-shedding. We don’t know whether his adult coat will shed so his new family should be prepared for shedding. His new family should be prepared to brush his coat regularly & have him groomed every 6-8 weeks or so. This is approximately $100 per groom.
ENERGY LEVEL: Sully is a very active puppy! He likes to run around & play with his foster siblings. 
DOGS: Sully loves other dogs. He is a very active, energetic puppy; if his new home has a dog it will need to be an active, tolerant dog. He doesn’t always know when to stop & leave the other dogs alone. If he has another dog in his new home it should be a dog that will be tolerant of his puppy play, but also be able to let him know when it’s time to stop.
CATS: unknown; no exposure to cats
KIDS: 12+ years old. Sully is a very energetic puppy, & he does not always know how to play with kids. In his prior home he would bite at the kid’s shirts & try to get them to play. 
CAR: Sully does OK in the car. He can get excited & bark, but once he settles down, he will sit & look out the window.
CRATE: OK in his crate. He knows that he needs to be in there when the humans leave, & as long as he is getting a treat he will go in. If there is no treat offered he will not be as excited to go in there. He would not do well being crated for large periods of time.
HOUSE TRAINED: Sully is mostly house trained. He will still have the occasional accident.
LEASH: Sully walks well on a leash with a harness. Without a harness (just a collar) he does pull more & doesn’t stop if there is something he wants to see, so we recommend a harness for him on all walks.
 
Sully is an F1 4 month old English Goldendoodle puppy who was surrendered to IDOG by his family. They consulted with a behaviorist trainer who felt he needs an experienced owner who can handle his dominant temperament & a family who is willing to put the time in to ensure he gets the appropriate amount of exercise & training in order to be a respectful dog. 

Here is what his foster family has to say about him:
Sully is very smart & learns very quickly; he can also learn bad habits very quickly as well. He remembers when he is allowed to “get away” with something & it can become a bad habit VERY quickly. He needs a home that will be consistent & firm with him. He has a very confident personality which can be great. But it can also lead to him thinking he is the boss of things if he does not have an owner that is consistent with him. 
 
Sully loves to play! He loves to tug and fetch & will bring a toy back right back to you. He does not always drop it right away. When he finally tires out, he will go lay down & rest. If you are near him, he will sometimes curl up in your lap for a quick nap. You should be OK with a large dog being a lap dog as we do think he’s going to be a big adult. 

He likes to play with his foster dog siblings, but does not always know when to stop, & he does not always get the hint. We have to distract him & play with him to get him to leave the other dogs alone. We think he will do fine in a home as an only dog as long as he has humans that will play with him & exercise his body & mind. If there is another dog in the home, it needs to be a younger, patient dog that will put up with his puppy shenanigans, but also not let Sully bully them.  
  
Sully is doing well with his potty training. As long as we are diligent about taking him outside, he does not have accidents. When we forget to take him out regularly he has accidents. He is still such a young pup that it is our fault when he has an accident because he is still learning. He will ring the bells to go out when he is calm & relaxed, but when he is excited & playing, he just forgets. He will need a home that will be patient with him as he learns. We do expect that he will probably have a setback when he goes to his new home, so his new owners should expect accidents, & be willing to work with him on his potty training. 
 
Sully is a normal energetic puppy! He can be strong-willed, so he needs an owner that will work with him. When he first came to us, he had a hard time being told “no” or not being allowed to do something he wanted to do. He would growl & snarl to try to get his way. He didn’t bite, but he sounded big & tough. He learned that if he acted tough & mean he would get away with things. He was basically a brat when first he came to us. He has learned that he is not the boss now & that he needs to listen.  This can very easily go back the other way – so he will need an experienced, patient dog owner that will continue to work with him. 
 
Sully needs help with his manners. He will put his front paws on the counter, or kitchen table if he thinks there is something up there for him. When he is told to get off, he doesn’t always get down right away – he will push his limits & make sure you are really serious about it first. He is always testing the waters. He will need to be taken to formal training & worked with until he learns the rules.  

He will needs to be crated when no one is home.  He does well in the crate as long as he is getting rewarded for going in. When we come home, he will bark & jump around in excitement to get out of the crate. Since we do not want him to think he gets to come out by acting like that, we will usually ignore him until he calms down, or ask him to sit. Once he sits & is calm, we will let him out of the crate. 

Sully has been allowed to sleep out of the crate at night in the room with his foster parents. He will lay down on the dog bed & curl up for the night. If he hears a noise, he will bark to let you know that something is concerning to him. Once he knows it’s ok, he will go back to bed. His new family should understand that he is still a small puppy & there are things he has not experienced yet. He still has a lot to learn, but we think with proper training & socialization, he is going to be an amazing companion as he gets matures 

Sully is a typical excitable puppy; he is up for whatever you have planned!! He does jump (we expect this at his young age) As long as his new owners will be willing to work with him, we think he will be easily trained. 

Sully has learned how to be more affectionate since he has been with us. When he first came to us, he did not like to be picked up, or kissed. He would growl & snarl. Now that he has learned some boundaries & that affection is good, he does great! He does not mind if we pick him up & when we kiss our other dogs on the head, he will come over & stick his head in to get his head kisses too! He needs a home that will continue the training that has been started. As long as the training is continued, he will continue on his way to being an amazing dog! 

Sully is very food motivated, which helps with training - he has never shown any food aggression at all, but he does like to eat! He will sit & wait until his foster siblings are finished eating. As soon as they walk away from their bowls, he will run over to check & see if there is any food left - he always acts like he is starving, but he is just a growing puppy. He is vaccinated, microchipped, crate trained & mostly house trained. He is heartworm negative & is current on heartworm, flea/tick preventives. He is not neutered yet & we will require his new owners get him neutered by the age of 9 months.
 	
IDOG will hold a $100 refundable training deposit to encourage his family to go through training to help him be successful in his new home. Since 2006, we have found that when an adopted dog goes through training with its new family it strengthens their bond & gives the adopted dog more confidence & security. The training deposit will be refunded upon proof of training.
 
ADOPTION FEE: $600 + $100 refundable training deposit to be refunded upon proof of training classes + $200 neuter deposit to by 9 months of age
